<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Opuntia littoralis </i>is a sprawling cactus that grows up to 1.5 m tall. As with other platyopuntias, plants have flattened stems with spines. Roots are shallow and laterally extensive. Fruits are fleshy and edible at maturity and are covered with barbed spines. Plants reproduce by seeds, layering, and sprouting from segments separated from the parent plant. Small mammals consume the fruits and disperse the seeds and stems (Johnson 2000b). <br/>
<br/>
We placed stands of various cactus taxa in this alliance due to both similarity and uncertainly of identification. The name of the alliance has been updated since the publication of the 2009 book, where it was cited as the "<i>Opuntia littoralis</i> Shrubland Alliance", to reflect this definition.  Many chollas (<i>Cylindropuntia</i>) and platyopuntias (<i>Opuntia</i>) occur along the southern California coast (Parfitt and Gibson 1993): <i>C. californica </i>var. <i>californica </i>and var. <i>parkeri, C. prolifera, O. ficus-indica, O. littoralis, O. oricola, O. xoccidentalis, </i>and <I>O. </I>x<i>vaseyi </i>(a hybrid complex involving <i>O. littoralis </i>and <i>O. phaeacantha</i>). The hybrids are morphologically variable. <I>O. </i>x<i>occidentalis </i>( <i>O. littoralis </i>x (<i>O. engelmannii</i> x  <i>O. phaeacantha</i>) and <I>O. </i>x<i>demissa </i>( <i>O. ficus-indica </i>hybrids) forms thickets that can dominate hillsides of coastal scrub and chaparral. Do not take these thickets lightly when considering sampling them. <br/>
<br/>
Dense stands of <i>O. littoralis </i>and <i>O. oricola </i>provide critical habitat for endemic animal and plant species on the mainland and on the Channel Islands: the coastal cactus wren (Solek and Szijj 2004), California gnatcatcher (Mock 2004), island night lizard, island sage sparrow, and several island snails (Junak 2004); <i>Castilleja grisea </i>and <i>Eriogonum crocatum </i>(CNPS list 1B plants); <i>Agave shawii, Bergerocactus emoryi, </i>and <i>Ferocactus viridescens </i>(CNPS list 2 plants); and <i>Calochortus catalinae </i>(a CNPS list 4 plant). <br/>
<br/>
Do not confuse stands of this alliance in San Diego Co. and on the southern Channel Islands with those with <i>Agave shawii </i>and <i>Bergerocactus emoryi. </i>They have more floristic affinities with the <i>Bergerocacto emoryi-Agavetum shawii </i>described by Peinado et al. (2007) for Baja California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
