<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Moderate or even low-severity fires can top-kill <i>Opuntia</i>. Although aboveground tissues easily die when burned, some fleshy stem segments usually survive low- to moderate-severity fire and resume growth. Plants regenerate by sprouting from the root crown, by the layering of unburned or partially burned pads, and from seeds dispersed to the site by animals. Frequent fires appear to reduce populations (Johnson 2000b). 

Stands on the northern Channel Islands (Johnson and Rodriguez 2001) show high cover of annual non-native <i>Bromus rubens </i>and other flashy fire fuels. Stands are variable with component succulent species throughout all the Channel Islands (Junak et al. 2007). Although fire is detrimental to most cacti (Nobel 1988), stands of <I>O. </I>x<i>occidentalis </i>often survive fires because they form large thickets. Plants have weak junctions, increasing the hybrid’s ability to reproduce vegetatively (Bobich and Nobel 2001). Our observations immediately after fires in Orange Co. suggest that cacti in dense <i>Opuntia </i>thickets sprout quickly after crown fire. Moderate fire return intervals may promote an increase in stand size relative to other non-succulent coastal scrubs.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (10-50 years)
				
