    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-j). Stands occur widely south of Santa Barbara Co. Stands in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) and the coastal hills in central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) include <i>Opuntia</i> hybrids. The densest stands appear to be dominated by <i>O. littoralis,</i> and more open stands with <i>O. oricola.</i> These open stands are ecologically similar to the others. Stands on the Channel Islands include <i>Bergerocactus emoryi, O. littoralis, O. oricola,</i> and <i>Cylindropuntia prolifera</i> (Junak et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf, Bj-l, Bn). Stands occur in the western foothills including central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) and the Perris Valley area of western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Historical accounts of vegetation on the Channel Islands (Junak 2007) suggest that cover of <i>Opuntia-</i>dominated scrubs increased with livestock browsing and grazing since the late nineteenth century. Currently, with a combination of biological control and reduced browsing intensity, these stands are relatively few today. On the mainland, stands have increased in density and number over the past several decades. These increases may be the result of shorter fire return intervals, grazing, brush clearing, or successful hybridization and vegetative reproduction of different <i>Cylindropuntia </i>and <i>Opuntia</i>. </div>
</div>

    

    

